<<<<<Directory Structure>>>>> These paths exist inside the container, empty by default — bind your own folders onto them so the container can read your files and write results back out:

        /code            your training/eval scripts
        /data            your input datasets
        /output          checkpoints and logs get written here
        /model           pretrained weights / cache directory
        /scratch         node-local scratch space (temp files, not kept)

        Also automatically available, no --bind needed:
        $HOME            your normal home directory
        /tmp             temp space

<<<<</Directory Structure>>>>>
========================================================================================
<<<<<Basic Flags>>>>> A handful of flags cover almost everything you'll need day to day:

        --nv                  Give the container access to your NVIDIA GPU(s).
                              Use it any time you're doing GPU work. Omit it
                              for CPU-only execution.

        --bind src:dst        Make a folder on your machine visible inside the
                              container at path dst. This is how the container
                              sees your code, data, and writes results back out.
                              Repeat the flag to bind more than one folder:
                                --bind /my/code:/code --bind /my/data:/data

        --env KEY=VALUE       Set an environment variable inside the container
                              for this run only, e.g. --env CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES=0

        (For the full list of options, see: apptainer help exec)

<<<<</Basic Flags>>>>>
========================================================================================
<<<<<Modes>>>>> There are four ways to use this container: run it plainly, exec a specific command, shell in interactively, or launch it as a background instance.

        RUN — start a built-in mode
        --------------------------------
        Launches a pre-built mode that ships with the container (e.g. jupyter).
        You don't point it at a script — you just pick the mode and it starts.
        The mode name goes at the end of the command.

          apptainer run --nv --bind /my/code:/code container.sif <mode>

        EXEC — run your own commands and scripts
        --------------------------------
        Runs a single command, or one of your own scripts (like train.py),
        inside the container. This is how you do actual work — bind in your
        code and data, set any env vars you need, and point exec at what to run.

          apptainer exec --nv --bind /my/code:/code --bind /my/data:/data \
            container.sif python /code/train.py

          # Multiple GPUs on one node
          apptainer exec --nv --bind /my/code:/code container.sif \
            torchrun --nproc_per_node=2 /code/train.py

          # Jupyter Lab, reachable via SSH tunnel
          apptainer exec --nv --bind /my/code:/code container.sif \
            jupyter lab --ip=0.0.0.0 --no-browser --port=8888 --notebook-dir=/code
          # then from your laptop:
          ssh -L 8888:<compute-node>:8888 <you>@<login-node>
          # open http://localhost:8888

        SHELL — drop into an interactive prompt
        --------------------------------
        Starts an interactive shell inside the container. No command runs
        automatically — useful for inspecting the environment, checking
        installed packages, or running things manually.

          apptainer shell --nv --bind /my/code:/code container.sif
          # Type `exit` to leave.

        INSTANCE — run the container as a persistent background service
        --------------------------------
        Starts the container detached, so it keeps running (e.g. a long
        training job or a Jupyter/TensorBoard server) after you disconnect.

          apptainer instance start --nv --bind /my/code:/code \
            container.sif torch-job

          apptainer exec instance://torch-job python /code/train.py

          apptainer instance list
          apptainer instance stop torch-job

<<<<</Modes>>>>>
========================================================================================
<<<<<Installing Extra Packages>>>>> You can `pip install` something new right inside a running container — it will work for that session. But the container filesystem resets on every fresh run, so anything you installed is gone next time, unless you use an overlay:

        apptainer overlay create --size 1024 overlay.img
        apptainer shell --nv --overlay overlay.img --bind /my/code:/code container.sif
        pip install <package>

        Reuse the same overlay.img next time to see the package again.

<<<<</Installing Extra Packages>>>>>
========================================================================================
<<<<<More Help & Testing>>>>> For the full list of built-in modes, flags, and usage details:

        apptainer run-help container.sif

To check that the container is intact and working:

        apptainer test container.sif

To also confirm the GPU is being picked up correctly, add --nv:

        apptainer test --nv container.sif

